segments.text: There's part of it that's good.
I can go ahead with the rest of it.
Another reason I decided to go to Texas A&M was because of the fact that it was a less expensive school than most of the others.
And I especially liked the idea of military training.
And I had been assured by some of my friends who were already at A&M that I could probably get a part-time job.
Now, that's it.
But after I came to Texas A&M, I had some difficulty because there were more students wanting jobs than they had jobs for.
And I had some difficulty, but I did real well in my freshman year and not so well in my sophomore year because I did spend quite a bit of time at an odd time job.
And I didn't have time to study.
But I made all that work up the next summer.
and finished my degree on time without any difficulty.
And I retained my commission in the Reserve Corps until World War II started.
And I mobilized with the 36th Division in November 1940.
Because I went to summer camp during the summertime, you see, and did my regular schoolwork.
uh in fall and spring and attended some summer schools.

I for instance got my master's degree at Texas A&M in 1928 by going to school while I was teaching at Hearn and coming down here every Saturday for conferences with the head of my department and chairman of my committee and I did all my dissertation work in between times.
So when I came back and
At the beginning of the second summer, I had completed all the research and done some of the typing.
So I finished the typing in June and had approved by the committee and completed the degree in August.
And I took some special courses at North Texas State.
It was called Teacher College then, I believe.
I did this because I was teaching some special work in the Temple Junior College, which prepared students for teacher certificates in health and physical education field.
And you want to just continue this military thing, or how much do you want?
Well, I want to ask what people you remember while you were a student here, who you were closely associated with, or any particular professors that made an impression on you?
There were three students that helped me more than any others while I was a freshman.
One of them was O.P.
Weiland, who was commander of my unit, which was the band.
You were in the band.
I took field artillery military training, but I lived with the band because I played an instrument in it.
And O.P.
Weiland was most helpful to all freshmen.
And I had another man who was Nat Turner, who was a junior at the time.
And he helped us with our academic work primarily.
If we needed help, we went to him.
And I had another one named Paul Washburn.
Incidentally, Nat Turner and Paul Washburn both live in Houston now.
And O.P.
Weiland retired as a lieutenant general from the tactical air forces.
Washburn was particularly good because he knew how to keep the freshmen pumped up when they got discouraged and down in the dumps.
He spent quite a bit of time with freshmen who were discouraged and wanted to go home.
And he tried also to keep the Stoutmore from hazing the freshmen.
I remember especially Dr.
I think they called him Dr. D.B.
Cofer.
I'm not sure he was a doctor.
But he was in the English department.
And he made his class work very interesting.
And he'd help us in our study time.
Any night we wanted to, we could meet him.
And he'd help us, not just with English, but other courses too.
And I had another professor in the drawing area named Dudley Baker.

I think Dudley died a few years ago, but he was especially helpful in advising us about student employment and how to study and how to retain what we got in the classroom and how to take notes and things of this sort.
And I never did forget what he taught me.
And then I had a Professor A. Mitchell, who was head of the, I think they called it engineering drawing at the time.
And he took some kind of a special interest in me, and I never did know why, except he had a son in school at the same time I was, a freshman.
And we used to visit quite often, and I'd go down to the house with this boy, and Professor A. Mitchell got interested in me.
And then I had one other professor named Sugareff, S-U-G-A-R-E-F-F, who was
in my opinion, one of the best history teachers I ever had.
And so inspired me with belief in America that I was one of those demons on patriotism after I got through with his courses in American history.
And I've never gotten over that, which I think helped me a great deal in my work at A&M, really.
Now, there were some other teachers, but I can't remember all their names at this time.
For instance, I had a chemistry teacher that was the most complete teacher I believe I ever had.
But he was patient with all students.
And if students started lagging behind, he'd require them.
He didn't ask them, but he forced them to come in and get extra help until he pulled himself up.
And I think I learned more about teaching from this one professor.
And I'm sorry I can't even think of his name.
This is awful.
But he had all the good qualities of a good teacher, in my opinion.
And I had some good math teachers, too.
This one math teacher that I can't think of his name was excellent.
And that's the reason I ended up teaching mathematics.
And all the time I taught in public school, I specialized in mathematics.
Taught some science classes, but preferred the mathematics because I thought I was better qualified.
You said you were in the band then.
Can you compare the band then to, say, today?
Yes.
We had about 65 pieces in the band and lived in old Milner Hall.
And the Cigna Corps lived in part of the building.
We had a real good bandmaster.
I thought pretty good, real good band, 65 piece band.
We practiced four nights a week for an hour.
And we participated in all ceremonies the cadet corps had on Saturdays.
They had a ceremony every Saturday, except rainy day.
And we participated in all kind of parades and things where the whole corps met out here in the afternoon.
Did you go on corps trips?
Went on corps trips.
We made a trip every year.
I was in the band to the Fort Worth Fat Stock Show.
And while we were there, we played street concerts in the high schools and colleges in that area and played out at the Stock Show Pavilion every afternoon and every night.
for a week.
And we made some trips to places like Baylor College at Belton.
I think they call it Mary Harden Baylor now.
And we went to places like Navasota and played concerts.
And then we played on the campus during the early school year, fall and up till cold weather.
a Sunday afternoon concert out in front of Speedle Hall every Sunday afternoon.
And incidentally, these programs were broadcast on an old radio station here on the campus.
I kind of wish they'd go back to Sunday afternoon concerts.
I've always enjoyed those.
Anything that really stands out about your band experiences?
Anything that's humorous or interesting or sticks with you?
Not especially.
It made it a little bit tough because this hour of practice we did at night, for instance, was extra.
And then we had to spend about an hour and a half every Saturday morning in a formal guard mount or battalion parade or something.
They had a different unit have a ceremony every Sunday, and we always had to play.
And then we had to play these Sunday afternoon concerts, and all these things were extra time-consuming.
I had some difficulty, but I had some of the best friends I ever had anywhere in the band, because we were close together.
We participated with each other in everything.
Even our intramurals were by band.
We didn't do like a lot of other units did.
And I remember that my little sister died when I was a freshman, and I didn't even have that money to go home.
before I knew what was happening and they had enough money for me to buy a railroad ticket.
And when I came back, I brought money from my father and they wouldn't take it because they wanted to help me this much.
And I have never forgotten that, of course.
And I had real good help from people like Paul Waxman and Nat Turner and O.P.
Wallin.
Now we had some
Difficult is mainly because of the fact that some of the military people didn't want us to spend this extra time with the band.
They wanted us to spend all of our time with the military unit.
And in fact, one of the captains, who was my supervisor, told me he wanted me to drop out of the band so I could devote all my time to military tactics.
And I didn't especially like this, and I didn't.
I stayed with the band all four years.
I'm glad.
That's great.
And I don't know of anything else, really.
Did you work?
You said you worked while you were a student.
Yes.
Could you tell me what?
I worked for the ground maintenance department, digging ditches and flower beds and mowing grass, 25 cents an hour.
I was going to ask you how much.
Yes, 25 cents an hour.
And then I was fortunate enough to get a job waiting tables in Speedy Hall when I was in the second sophomore semester.
And I believe that we got the equivalent of our board, which was about $20, $25 a month.
And then in addition to that, I worked some on Saturday for cotton seed and corn research out at the experiment station.
I did some work out there for Dr. Mangelsdorf and the corn breeding and also for
Dave Killough and the Cotton Breeding.
Now who helped you?
Did you go looking for work or was there a place on campus where this information was available then?
There really wasn't much place to look.
The secretary of the president handled whatever loans were made and they didn't actually make a loan they just had you sign a note and you paid it out twenty dollars, thirty dollars a month.
And this man was Mr. S.G. Bailey
And you could ask him for a job, but he really didn't help anybody.
He was Secretary of the President, and he handled all these notes and things, but he didn't have time.
So you had to go on your own.
I got my jobs, I got all my jobs on my own by going directly to the people that hired me.
I see.
How did you know where to go then?
Could you ask?
I'd ask, like over there in Band Hall, I asked Captain Weiland, where can I go find a job?
This Mr. Hensel is in charge of the ground maintenance.
He hired all the lawn mowers and the ditch diggers and the flower bed keepers and things of this sort.
And he showed me where his office was.
So I went to see Mr. Hensel.
He's the man that hired me to do this work.
And at that time, incidentally, most of the faculty lived in houses on the outskirts of the campus.
And the college kept up a lot of these yards.
And I don't know how they decided which ones.
I remember two or three of those professors' houses that I kept yards for.
Do you remember the names of them?
One of them was Ed Williams down here on Joe Routt Boulevard, right back where old Guy Hall was.
I don'tRuthers had her down.
And then there was a head of the rural education department, Pop Hughes, W.L.
Hughes, lived there on the corner.
right across the street from Coliseum now, where the parking lot is.
I mowed his yard once a week.
And Mr. Hensel paid me, of course.
I don't even know for sure where they did it.
I went to Sergeant King, who was the man in charge of the student labor in Dining Hall.
He was a sergeant in the Army, and they paid him actually for this duty with the permission from the Army.
So I went to Sergeant King and told him I needed a job working.
I knew this didn't take a lot of time when you studied and everything, because right at mealtime, that's when you had to eat.
So he put me on the list, and he and Sergeant Tyler, they were the two men that helped get me a job on the dining hall staff.
And I worked over there until I graduated.
You worked three years there?
Mm-hmm.
I wonder how many people have gone through A&M waiting tables.
I guess a whole lot.
A whole bunch.
Yeah, that's right.
And after you graduated from A&M, you went on then to Hearn, then to teach math and coach.
Now, we were talking about your beginning of your Army days, 1940.
Was the 36th Division called active duty in 1940?
36th Division was called active duty on November 29, 1940.
And that means since you held a reserve commission in that unit, you were activated.
Yes.
Now, actually, the 36th Division was a Texas National Guard division.
And we had a National Guard company in my town, Temple.
Old Company D, the 143rd Infantry.
Soon after we mobilized, I was sent with about 25 or 30 other officers from our division to a three-month school at Fort Benning, Georgia.
And when we returned from Georgia, we went to Camp Bowie in Brownwood.
where the 36th Division had moved to.
I stayed with them as a company commander, and I was promoted while I was in school.
At the time you were mobilized, what was your rank when you were mobilized?
When we mobilized, I was a first lieutenant, and I was promoted to the rank of captain.
You see, back at that time, you couldn't be promoted unless there was a vacancy.
Now, I'd been a first lieutenant, I think, six or seven years, which was longer than normal, but they didn't have a vacancy.
So my captain got promoted to a majority.
And while I was in school, they made me a captain.
When I came back, I commanded a company, and they transferred me to another company.
But for some internal reasons in the regiment, they had some problems out there.
But I stayed with them until January 1942.
And in January 1942, I was assigned to a cadre to form a new division.
and went back to Fort Benning, Georgia for one month and was assigned to 82nd Infantry Division, which was commanded by General Bradley.
And my regimental commander was an A&M graduate, 1918 class.
Can you think of his name?
Colonel Easley.
Easley.
Called him Spec Easley.
Incidentally, he became a Brigadier General and was killed in Okinawa.
Then we left Fort Bend, Georgia in February and moved to Camp Claiborne, Louisiana.
And this was a brand new camp.
So we got in about 18,000 draftees and started training them first week in March.
In August of that year, we were transferred.

We were made into a motorized division, and the 1st of September made into the 1st Airborne Division, at which time I was sent to Fort Leavenworth with five other officers, especially to study the command functions and to specialize in airborne tactics.

When I got out of school in November, I rejoined the division which had moved from Claiborne, Louisiana to Fort Bragg, North Carolina, so we could get the airborne training and get ready to go overseas.
Now, this division is what now?
82nd.
It's still the 82nd.
It came from the 82nd Infantry to 82nd Airborne.
Right.
Okay.
And you perhaps remember the 82nd because it's where we started York's outfit, World War I. I called it AA, or All-American Division.
And we trained at Fort Braille, North Carolina and went to North Africa in early May 1943.
Landed at Casablanca on the 10th of May.
Made an amphibious landing there.
No, we made a, we went because the invasion had already started there and we were trying to get to North Africa in time to cut off the retreat of the Germans.
And we
unloaded our ships and went to Usta, which was about, I guess, 150 miles from Casablanca.
And we trained there until about when we got to Usta, the Germans had escaped.
They were all gone.
They had gotten into Sicily and Italy.
So they weren't in a particular point.
So then they sent us down at Usta to prepare for the Sicilian invasion.
And we were the assault division with one British division on Sicily.
a short time after Fourth of July.
We tried to make it on the Fourth of July, but we didn't quite make it.

And my particular outfit didn't go to, essentially because the Navy and the 45th Division shut down about 25 of our planes on the incoming echelon, and we lost about 575 paratroopers, and so they called off our part because I belonged to a gladiator regiment.
And it's good because if we'd have gone, we'd have probably had about 60% casualties.
So we went amphibiously.
And we didn't know much about what we were doing, but we went amphibiously.
And then we went from Sicily.
Where did you land in Sicily?
We landed at Gela, G-E-L-A.
And how long were you in Sicily?
We were in Sicily about a month and a half or two months.
And then we loaded up to go to Italy.
But we got some bad information from the Italian Army, so we had to call off our parachute operation.
We were to load two parachute regiments on the beach.
We did send one parachute battalion up to Avelina, and they got chopped to all the pieces.
But we finally sent
We finally did send two regiments, but they just jumped on the beach.
Not as a combat exercise, just a quick method of getting there.
We sent the rest of the troops in by LCTs, landing craft.
We landed on Red Beach, just a little bit out of Salerno.
Then we transferred over to Maori and joined up with the Rangers, Darby's Rangers.
Not General Rogers, but Colonel Darby.
And we stayed with him until we reached Naples.
And then we made, we, the 82nd was the occupying division for Naples until Thanksgiving.
We got to Naples on the 4th of October of 1943.
And we got orders, very quick orders, to go to Ireland to get ready for overlord operation in Normandy in 1944.
Back up just a minute and see if there's a quick one here.
Is there anything that sticks out in the Italian campaign?
Any things of interest?
Any contacts you may have had with Omar Bradley or anybody that was involved?
Patton?
Patton was in Sicily.
He didn't go to Italy.
Anything that may have happened that might be of interest or a little known fact?
Yes, I remember, well, I bumped in first to quite a large number of ex-Aggies.
Oh, I'm sure.
With the various divisions occupying Sicily and Italy.
And I had quite a number of contacts with John Clark, Mark Clark, Fifth Army.
And I did have some contacts with John Patton.
in the initial steps of this invasion, first part of it.
And I knew quite a number of British officers, mainly because of the fact that on all these airborne operations we tried to coordinate so we wouldn't have any conflict of priorities.
And I knew quite a number of them.
Did you ever get a chance to meet Montgomery?
No, I never did meet Montgomery.
I saw General Bradley a good number of times.
Your impressions of Bradley?
In my opinion, Bradley was sort of a school teacher type of guy, really.
Had a wonderful memory and was one of the most complete tacticians I ever saw.
And then I found out later, up in the
middle of the war that he was not only a tactician, but he was worldwide.
He had all the political aspects of this thing in his command.
Just listen to some of those guys like that.
He was one of Eisenhower's chief advisors, I found out, because I know two or three times when up in the Ardennes, for instance,
Montgomery didn't want to do what General Ridgway wanted to do.
Ridgway was our corps commander, you see, because Ridgway was one of the old West Point boys that was hard as nails, but an expert on tactics.
And he commanded 82nd, and then later, when he organized the 18th Airborne Corps, he became the corps commander as a part of the 1st Allied Airborne Army.
and it was called Allied Airborne because it had British and American.
Bradley was, he knew what he wanted to do, and he thought it all out ahead of time, and he was fast.
He didn't have to fool around two or three days to make a decision.
He made it.
He was sympathetic, and he was patient, but if a guy was slumping off or cowardly, he had no sympathy with him.
I thought he controlled Montgomery almost as well as I did, really.
He just had to say, we're not going to do it that way, Monty, because it's not tactically sound.
We're going to do it this way.
And that's it.
That's fine.
No more discussion about it at all.
And I saw him do that up there at Harzay in Belgium.
Did you have any contact with Patton that you can remember anything about him?
Not very much.

I had to report to General Patton's headquarters one time as a representative of the division staff to find out what the details of the attack were going to be, because General Ridgeway had been told that he might be called on to supplement this attack, even though we knew we weren't going to make an airborne attack.
We were going to be used as ground troops.
So I had to go up there, and I spent the whole day

talking to his staff first, and then when he gave his combat orders to his, I had to identify myself as it, because they'd all talked to just any and everybody, but he gave his combat orders for the next day's operation while I was there, and then I went back with this in my mind.
I wasn't allowed to write any of this down or take any map marks or anything, but I had to memorize all this and take it back to General Ridgway, and we had a code word that
If they wanted us to go, all they did is phone him this one word, and then we went.
But we didn't go.
Really, that's the only contact I had with him directly.
Now, I did hear him make three speeches, one in Africa and two in England.
I heard him make that speech he got so much fame for on the fourth day of June, which was printed in magazines all around.
They used some of the excerpts in this Patton story on the movie.
Just the one where he left the Russians out or whatever it was?
They were still trying to cover up for him.
Well, actually, I think they didn't allow any newspaper people at this meeting.
That's what I was told anyhow.
I know when he got through his speech, he told us, now there won't be any mention made by anybody in this outfit that you've seen Patton or heard him.
And the Army was trying to keep him covered up.
They wanted to make it look like he'd gone back to the United States.
But he was a good commander.
Good field commander.
Oh, yeah.
You see, and one reason I know that is because when we were down in Arden's campaign, we had 101st Airborne Division cut off completely at Bastogne.
And General Ridgway was commanded 82nd.
and the 101st.
And he called on Patton to try to relieve the pressure on the 101st, and he did.
He did eventually.
Wheel 90 degrees or something.
Right.
I know my father was in the 26th YB and made that wheel.
Now, you talked about going to Ireland for Overlord.
Could you tell us a little bit about the preparations for Overlord?
Yes.
About three weeks before we left Italy to go to Ireland, I was made Division G-4 with supply logistics.
And I had to get busy and relearn some things I'd forgotten.
We had supplies in Italy, Sicily, and North Africa.
And we had carried enough parachutes for three complete airborne operations.
We had to get all this stuff loaded.
And when we took off, we had to load out in the harbor because the harbor in Naples was full of something ships, or battered ships.
We took off by loading out in the harbor and were heckled and harassed considerably by the German bombers until we got to O-Ran, I guess it was.

And we joined up with a British outfit, and I think there were about 50 ships in the convoy that went through the Straits of Gibraltar at night so they wouldn't be able to see too much of what we were doing.
And we headed out for the middle of the Atlantic and headed due north and ran into one storm and one or two submarine pikes.
So we had to change course and skirt them.
We had bummer escort all the time, B-17.
So it actually took us longer to get there than we thought.
We left, after we left, sailed out of Naples Harbor on the morning of the Monday before Thanksgiving.
And we hooked up at O-Ran for one day.
And we got to North Ireland, Belfast on the 10th of December.
It was cold and blue-bladed.
We'd gone all over the dang Atlantic
But we didn't lose anybody.
North Atlantic is something, isn't it?
We didn't lose a ship.
We ran into some submarine packs that were definitely identified, but we didn't lose any ships, which is good.
We landed in North Island, really, because there wasn't any space for us to land in England at that time.
We're about to North Island.
We landed at Belfast, and we were scattered from... We had one regiment at Ballymena, one at Cookstown,
our division headquarters, a small town about 20 miles out of Belfast.
I can't even think of the name of it now.
We had our parachute maintenance thing at a bomber base about 40 miles out of Belfast, because we had to get all those chutes off of those boats, ships.
and hang them up and dry them, because they'd been down in the hole a good while.
And we didn't know whether they were damaged or not, so we had to dry them all out.
Of course, it was colder and blue blazes in the North Island.
We did as much training as we could, but mainly we got the guys who were crippled, you know, rejuvenated.
We got replacements for the guys that we lost down there.
We got resupplied, and we found out a lot of things we'd done
in Africa, some of the equipment was inappropriate, some of it was not very efficient, so we had to remake a lot of our equipment.
We did most of that in Ireland.
For instance, could you give me an example?
Yes, we had a parachute company, a parachute maintenance company.
that had some real good experts in it.
They'd take these pieces of equipment, like a guy would go up with a radio pack on, and he'd jump with it on.
And to see how it got his, see if it fouled his rifle up, see how hard it was to take off as he hit the ground, how many of them were broken and all this.
So they found out that these pieces of equipment were either too loose or too tight.
Nearly all of them, they made it right
Patterson, but they just made them from blue pressure.
They didn't have them tested completely.
And we found on that operation down in Italy, for instance, a lot of the guys were getting their shroud lines fouled up with their rifles and bayonets.
And we always equipped each guy with at least two hand grenades in their big pockets.
And sometimes they got fouled up with the equipment.
And it made it real dangerous.
But we had two guys that were killed this way.
Pulled that pen out prematurely.
So all these tests were made by officers, incidentally, not by enlisted men.
But the officers would take this equipment up and jump out.
We had one major that jumped out as much as 10 times a day up there for weeks.
And when they'd come back, then we'd all meet.
Since I was a G4, they wouldn't do anything without my approval, and we had to buy some pieces of canvas and what do you call it?
Glove fasteners, for instance.
A lot of these things we had were those little things where you'd turn them, and you couldn't get them loose if they got jammed.
But these glove fasteners, you could pull it, and you couldn't keep them from coming in fast.
We had some other adjustments made on our parachute releases because some of the jams
were coming, you know, when a guy would get in on the ground or in a tree, he'd hit that button and it didn't release.
Couldn't get out of the chute except by cutting himself out with a gun.
Humpty-dumpty shroud lines to cut.
So we didn't want that to happen, and we also wanted to perfect some of our pathfinder equipment so that we could have a school with the Air Force people.

they're going to have to fly us and we want to get down where we're supposed to go and we we tested all that equipment and found a lot of it defective and deficient when you got on the ground it wouldn't light up the signals wouldn't operate well it's no good if it's not going to operate so we we we repacked a lot of our equipment and repatted a lot of it and made different facets and
unfasteners, where you put zippers on a lot of it, where it could be controlled easily.
We made over 100,000 pieces of equipment in North Ireland getting rid of this invasion.
So then in February, we went to England because they had built some new controlments in the Midlands, Greenham, right out of Leicester.
In fact, we had the division headquarters in the city park
Victoria Park in Leicester.
And then we had our field of operation for the invasion down at Greenham Commons, which was about 100 miles south.
So we started our training program by taking a battalion at a time, battalion of paratroopers and battalion gliders out with the Air Force people, pathfinders and all.
And we ran further tests on our pathfinder equipment by going out toward Norway and coming back in across the North Sea.
Coming in blind to see if we could actually home in on these stations.
Because we didn't do too good a job homing down on that Sicilian and Italian operation.
And we wanted us, well we had to have this Normandy operation good or it was going to be a failure.
So we did a lot of night practicing and
We assimilated as much as we could.
We got all of our plans and details ready.
And when we got ready for the invasion, we moved south with the glider units, because they couldn't be tugged all the way from north.
The paratroopers operated from their regular home bases.
And we sent out two American divisions and one British division, beginning about
11 o'clock on D-1, and then our glider, our gliders started out about midnight.
I was in the glider.
We left Greenham Commons in the particular glider that I was in.
My glider was the first one off.
And on that first lift, we only took 52 gliders and brought in 126 the next afternoon at 5 o'clock.
How many men to the gliders you were on?
We had 13, plus the pilot and co-pilot.
13 combat people.
Now we carried in some equipment too.
We carried in a few tank destroyers and a few heavier guns that we could use for small artillery because we had to have something to fight those tanks off with.
What were your thoughts going over it that if the landing didn't come off, I wonder if you all thought about you'd be stuck there?
Oh, yes.
If that crossed your mind.
Yes, we thought about that quite a bit.
Of course, some of us knew for months where we were going and when.
How many?
Not many?
Not very many, no.
So far as I know, the division staff were the only people that knew prior to a week before invasion time.
Now this, when I say division staff, the general and assistant general and chief of staff and the one, two, three, four.
We were the only ones.
What was your objective?
Our objective in Normandy operation, you're talking about division objective now.
Well, where you were going, your glider was on the way, and what was the particular destination?
Yes.
Well, my regiment.
And incidentally, don't forget, I was a division staff officer at the time we made the Normandy invasion.
You were G4 still.
I was a G4.
So I was on the general staff, and I had to be with him as much as possible, or close enough to him that he could contact me when he needed to know something about the supply situation.
The supply meant ammunition and medicine, whatever.
And we had enough.
supplies packed up in parachute bundles to make a resupply for three days.
Now this was about a hundred and ten times a day really.
It all packaged and loaded with proper colored chutes and everything.
And we had, and the quartermaster of course was trained with us because they had to do the kicking of the bundles out of the planes.
But our objective was to
